5. Subsystem Specifications

5.1 Airframe and Propulsion

5.1.1 Airframe

· Material: Carbon‑fiber reinforced polymer with titanium alloy high‑stress inserts.
· Configuration: Blended wing‑body with variable‑geometry wings.
  · Wingspan: 5.2 m (fully extended loiter) / 2.4 m (swept intercept).
  · Length: 4.5 m.
  · Height: 1.2 m.
· Morphing Mechanism: Electromechanical actuators with shape‑memory alloy backup; transition time ≤3 s.
· Stealth Features: Radar‑absorbent material coating, serpentine intake, internal weapons bay.

5.1.2 Propulsion

· Electric Motors: Two 150 kW ducted fans (rear‑mounted) for low‑noise loiter and taxi.
  · Power source: High‑density lithium‑sulfur batteries, 80 kWh capacity.
  · Endurance: 30 hours at 50 knots loiter speed.
· Ramjet Engine: One variable‑geometry ramjet (JP‑10 fuel) for supersonic dash.
  · Thrust: 20 kN at sea level, 10 kN at 60,000 ft.
  · Fuel capacity: 800 kg, providing 1,500 km intercept range.
· Thrust Vectoring: 2‑D nozzles (±20° deflection) for high agility.

5.2 Avionics and Sensors

5.2.1 Radar

· Type: Active Electronically Scanned Array (AESA), X‑band.
· Antenna: Nose‑mounted, 0.8 m diameter, 360° coverage via mechanical rotation.
· Performance:
  · Detection range: 250 km (RCS 1 m²), 100 km (RCS 0.01 m²).
  · Track while scan: 200 tracks simultaneously.
  · Modes: SAR, GMTI, weather avoidance.

5.2.2 Electro‑Optical/Infrared (EO/IR)

· Sensor: Multi‑spectral turret (visible, SWIR, MWIR, LWIR) with laser rangefinder/designator.
· Resolution: 4K visible, 1 MP IR.
· Field of View: 60° to 0.5° narrow.
· Stabilization: 5‑axis gyro‑stabilized, <5 µrad jitter.

5.2.3 LIDAR

· Type: Solid‑state flash LIDAR, 256×256 pixel array.
· Range: 5 km.
· Accuracy: 10 cm at 1 km.

5.2.4 Acoustic Sensor

· Array: 32‑microphone spiral array for gunshot/missile launch detection.
· Range: 10 km for small arms, 30 km for rocket launch.

5.2.5 Nuclear Detection

· Gamma Spectrometer: High‑purity germanium (HPGe) cryocooled.
· Neutron Detector: Helium‑3 tubes.
· Sensitivity: Detect 1 kg weapon‑grade plutonium at 500 m.

5.2.6 Navigation

· INS/GPS: Honeywell HG9900 with laser gyros.
· Backup: Vision‑based navigation (terrain relative, celestial) for GPS‑denied.
· ADS‑B In/Out: For airspace integration.

5.3 Computing and Processing

5.3.1 Photonic Processor

· Model: Lightmatter Envise‑2 (or equivalent).
· Architecture: 64×64 optical matrix multiplier array.
· Performance: 2 PFLOPS (equivalent) for matrix operations, 10 TOPS/W.
· Memory: 8 GB HBM2e, optically interfaced.
· Function: Real‑time sensor preprocessing, image recognition, radar signal processing.

5.3.2 Electronic Processor

· SoC: Xilinx Versal Premium (VP2802) with:
  · ARM Cortex‑A78 (8 cores) @ 2.2 GHz.
  · NVIDIA Ampere GPU (2048 CUDA cores).
  · FPGA fabric (2M logic cells).
· Performance: 100 TFLOPS (FP16), 200 TOPS (INT8).
· Memory: 32 GB LPDDR5, 256 GB/s.

5.3.3 Quantum Co‑processor

· Type: Superconducting gate‑model quantum processor (e.g., Rigetti Aspen‑M).
· Qubits: 80 qubits, with 5‑ms coherence.
· Cryostat: Compact pulse‑tube cooler, 10 mK operating temperature.
· Function: Solving trajectory optimization, quantum key distribution.

5.3.4 Storage

· Type: NVMe SSD, 2 TB, encrypted (AES‑256).
· Data Recorder: 4 TB high‑speed recorder for mission data.

5.4 Communication and Data Links

5.4.1 Quantum Key Distribution (QKD) Link

· Type: Free‑space QKD transmitter (BB84 protocol).
· Wavelength: 1550 nm.
· Range: 100 km line‑of‑sight (day), 200 km (night).
· Key Rate: 1 Mbps.

5.4.2 Tactical Data Links

· Link 16: Class 2H terminal.
· SATCOM: Ka‑band (30/20 GHz) with phased array antenna.
· UHF/VHF: Software‑defined radio for legacy waveforms.

5.4.3 Mesh Networking

· Protocol: IEEE 802.11ad (60 GHz) for high‑bandwidth UAV‑to‑UAV links.
· Range: 10 km.
· Data Rate: 2 Gbps.

5.4.4 IFF

· Mode 5/S: Combined interrogator/transponder.

5.5 Power and Thermal Management

5.5.1 Power System

· Primary Batteries: Lithium‑sulfur, 80 kWh, 1,500 Wh/kg.
· Ramjet Fuel: JP‑10, 800 kg.
· Solar Cells: Thin‑film gallium arsenide on wings, 2 kW peak.
· Power Distribution: 270 VDC bus for propulsion, 28 VDC for avionics.

5.5.2 Thermal Management

· Liquid Cooling: Pumped two‑phase cooling for electronics, rejecting heat to fuel or ram air.
· Cryocooler: Stirling cycle for quantum processor (10 K).
· Heat Exchangers: Skin heat exchangers on wings.

5.6 Software Architecture

5.6.1 Operating System

· Kernel: Linux 6.1 with PREEMPT_RT patches.
· Distribution: Yocto‑built, hardened with SELinux and IMA.
· Real‑Time Performance: Task latency <10 µs (measured).

5.6.2 Middleware

· DDS: Eclipse Cyclone DDS for real‑time data distribution.
· ROS2: For simulation and prototyping nodes.
· ZeroMQ: For low‑latency control messages.

5.6.3 AI Frameworks

· Training: TensorFlow 2.12, PyTorch 2.0 on cloud clusters.
· Inference: TensorRT for GPU, custom compiler for photonic processor.
· Reinforcement Learning: Ray RLlib 2.0.

5.6.4 Containerization

· Runtime: Docker/LXC with lightweight OS containers.
· Orchestration: Kubernetes (edge) for multi‑container management.

5.7 QUENNE Intelligence Layers (Software Modules)

Each layer is implemented as a set of containerized microservices with well‑defined APIs.

5.7.1 TRIAD AI (Human Authority)

· Michael (Ethical Engine):
  · Input: Threat data, proposed action, ROE database.
  · Output: Permissibility score (0‑1), explanation.
  · Algorithm: Hybrid symbolic‑neural network with formal verification.
  · Interface: REST API to HMI.
· Gabriel (Strategic Planner):
  · Input: Mission objectives, sensor data, airspace status.
  · Output: Updated mission plan, waypoints.
  · Algorithm: Hierarchical reinforcement learning (PPO).
· Rafael (Protective Intelligence):
  · Input: System telemetry, cyber alerts.
  · Output: Health status, evasive commands.
  · Algorithm: Anomaly detection (autoencoders).

5.7.2 Nuclear Intelligence (QNI)

· Input: Gamma/neutron spectra, radar tracks.
· Output: Nuclear threat probability, engagement authorization flags.
· Algorithm: Spectral fingerprint matching (CNN) + rule‑based logic.
· Failsafe: Requires two independent sensor confirmations and human approval.

5.7.3 Atomic Fusion Algorithm

· Input: Raw sensor data (radar, EO/IR, LIDAR, acoustic, external tracks).
· Output: Unified world model (objects with position, velocity, classification, covariance).
· Algorithm: Kalman filter bank + attention‑based fusion network.
· Update Rate: 100 Hz.

5.7.4 Booster Fusion Algorithm

· Input: Flight mode command, aerodynamic data, fuel state.
· Output: Actuator commands (wing sweep, thrust vectoring, throttle).
· Algorithm: Model predictive control (MPC) with online aerodynamic model learning.
· Transition Time: <2 s.

5.7.5 Hybrid Photonic‑Electronic AI

· Photonic Core: Executes low‑level vision and radar processing (e.g., FFT, convolution).
· Electronic Core: Runs high‑level reasoning and control.
· Coordination: Shared memory with low‑latency queue.

5.7.6 Engineering Algorithm

· Input: Strain/temperature/vibration from fiber‑optic sensors.
· Output: Structural health index, recommended flight limits.
· Algorithm: Finite element model updating + fatigue life prediction.
· Update Rate: 10 Hz.

5.7.7 Quantum Algorithm

· QKD Module: Interfaces with optical transceiver, generates encryption keys.
· Optimizer: Solves mixed‑integer programming for intercept trajectories using quantum annealing (or classical fallback).
· Random Number Generator: Quantum random number generator for cryptography.

5.7.8 Linux Core Algorithm

· Not a distinct algorithm but the hardened OS layer. Provides real‑time scheduling, security, and container isolation.

5.7.9 Cross‑Platform Abstraction

· HAL: Abstracts hardware details for sensor drivers, actuator interfaces.
· Middleware: DDS topics for all data streams, hardware‑agnostic.

